    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7b9a4c18-0ec7-4e11-8d29-a45ff252e69d",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 31-year-old woman who appears tired but otherwise well, dressed neatly in casual office attire and often keeping a pair of dark sunglasses within reach because bright light tends to worsen her headaches. During symptomatic periods she becomes quiet, prefers dim rooms, and limits conversation because noise and routine activity intensify the pain. She describes recurrent unilateral throbbing headaches that build over 1 to 2 hours, most often centered behind the right eye or temple, associated with nausea, photophobia, and phonophobia. The attacks occur several times per month and can last from part of a day to nearly two days, leaving her fatigued and cognitively slowed afterward.\n\nShe works full-time as a graphic designer, spending long hours on screens and often juggling tight deadlines. Her daily routine is somewhat irregular; she may skip breakfast when rushing to work and sometimes relies on coffee to compensate for poor sleep. She tries to stay active with evening yoga classes and weekend walks with a close friend, but migraine episodes frequently disrupt these plans. She lives with her partner in an urban apartment and has a supportive social circle, though she occasionally withdraws during severe attacks because she knows she will need silence and darkness.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys digital illustration, reading contemporary fiction, and caring for several houseplants. She drinks alcohol only socially and does not smoke. She has noticed that stress, sleep deprivation, prolonged screen exposure, and occasionally the days around menstruation seem to trigger headaches, though not every episode has an obvious precipitant. She keeps a phone-based symptom diary and has become increasingly concerned that the frequency of attacks is affecting both productivity and quality of life.\n\nIn conversation, {patientName} is thoughtful and articulate, but she expresses frustration that people sometimes dismiss her migraines as “just headaches.” She worries about planning work presentations and social events because the attacks are unpredictable. Despite this, she is motivated, health-conscious, and engaged in managing her symptoms, trying hydration, regular meals, and better sleep habits with partial success."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b7873275-13c5-44ae-8e03-ba781b218c5c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports episodic headaches since her early 20s, with clearer migraine features developing over the past several years. She has not had focal neurologic deficits, syncope, head trauma, fever, or recent infection associated with the headaches. There is no history suggesting secondary headache disorder, and she has never been hospitalized for migraine, though she has visited an urgent care clinic once in the past year for severe nausea and dehydration during a prolonged attack.\n\nHer past medical history is notable for mild intermittent asthma and seasonal allergic rhinitis. She denies hypertension, diabetes, seizure disorder, clotting disorder, or prior stroke. She uses a combined hormonal contraceptive and takes over-the-counter ibuprofen intermittently for menstrual cramps or headache relief, generally fewer than 8 to 10 days per month. She has no history of pregnancy complications. Sleep is often reduced during busy work periods, averaging 5 to 6 hours on weekdays, and she acknowledges that skipped meals and heavy screen use often precede symptoms.\n\n{patientName} does not smoke or use recreational drugs. She drinks 1 to 2 cups of coffee daily and alcohol about 1 to 2 times per month. Exercise is irregular but includes yoga and walking. She has never had neurosurgery or major chronic neurologic illness. Her main goals are to better predict attacks, reduce functional impairment, and avoid medication overuse."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}